## Async tasks — measured duration in navbar + START/END logs

Context: Long-running operations tracked by the in-memory `TaskManager`
(ontology generation, auto-mapping, metadata load, triplestore sync,
quality checks, etc.) had no visible elapsed time. The navbar hourglass
showed only "5m ago" against `created_at` and the bell completion toast
gave no idea how long the run took. Logs printed `Task X started` /
`Task X completed: …` with no consistent START/END marker and no
duration, making it hard to grep `ontobricks.log` for performance
regressions.

The fix wires a single source-of-truth duration through the model, the
log lines and the UI:

- Backend exposes `Task.duration_seconds()` (live for running/pending,
  frozen at `completed_at − started_at` for terminal tasks) and
  serialises it in `Task.to_dict()` so every consumer of `GET /tasks/`
  sees the same number the logs print.
- TaskManager rewrites its lifecycle log lines to a `START task <id>
  [<type>] — <name>` / `END task <id> [<type>] <verb> in <duration>`
  pattern at INFO level, easy to grep with `grep -E "START task|END
  task"`.
- The navbar hourglass dropdown now shows a live ticking elapsed time
  for running rows (1 s timer, no extra polling) and the bell completion
  toast appends `(in 1m 23s)` next to the task name.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/task_manager/models.py
   - `Task.duration_seconds()` — new computed method. Uses
     `started_at → completed_at` when both are set, falls back to
     `created_at` if the worker never called `start_task`, and uses
     `now` as the right-hand side for active tasks so the UI can show
     a live timer. Returns `None` only when no usable timestamp exists,
     never negative (clamped to 0).
   - `Task.to_dict()` — extended with `"duration_seconds": <float|None>`
     so the field is part of the public JSON shape returned by
     `GET /tasks/` and `GET /tasks/{id}`.

2. src/back/core/task_manager/TaskManager.py
   - New module-level helper `_format_duration(seconds)` returning
     compact strings: `"450ms"`, `"2.40s"`, `"1m 23.5s"`, `"1h 5m"`.
   - `start_task` log line rewritten to `START task <id> [<type>] —
     <name>: <message>` (or `... (step 1/N: <step>)` when the task has
     steps). Same INFO level as before.
   - `complete_task` log line rewritten to `END task <id> [<type>]
     completed in <duration> — <message>`.
   - `fail_task` keeps its existing `logger.error(... failed after
     <duration>: <error>)` for visibility but additionally emits the
     unified `END task <id> [<type>] failed in <duration>` INFO line so
     a single `grep "END task"` finds every terminal transition.
   - `cancel_task` log line rewritten to `END task <id> [<type>]
     cancelled in <duration>`.

3. src/front/static/global/js/task-tracker.js
   - New helpers `formatDuration(startISO, endISO)`,
     `computeTaskDuration(task)` and `formatSeconds(seconds)` shared
     by the active-task panel and the bell. They prefer the
     server-supplied `duration_seconds` when present so the value
     shown in the UI matches the value the backend logged, and fall
     back to client-side computation otherwise.
   - `renderTaskItem` — the right-column label now shows the live
     elapsed time for running rows (`<small data-task-elapsed>` so the
     ticker can target it) and keeps `getTimeAgo(created_at)` for
     pending rows.
   - `tickRunningDurations()` — re-renders only the small
     `data-task-elapsed` text nodes once per second from `initTaskTracker`,
     so the timer advances visibly between the 3 s active polls
     without re-fetching.
   - `notifyTaskTransition` — completed / failed / cancelled bell
     toasts append `(in <duration>)` next to the task name.
   - `formatDuration` is exposed on `window.formatTaskDuration` for
     other modules.

4. tests/test_task_manager.py
   - `TestDuration`: covers `_format_duration` bucket boundaries,
     monotonic growth of pending/running durations, frozen duration
     after `complete_task`, and presence of `duration_seconds` in
     `to_dict()`.
   - `TestStartEndLogging`: a `task_logs` fixture attaches the caplog
     handler directly to `ontobricks.core.task_manager.TaskManager`
     (the `ontobricks` logger has `propagate=False` once
     `LogManager.setup` has run, which it does in the full suite via
     other tests) and asserts the four lifecycle paths emit the
     expected START/END markers with `completed in` / `failed in` /
     `cancelled in` substrings.

Modified files:
- src/back/core/task_manager/models.py
- src/back/core/task_manager/TaskManager.py
- src/front/static/global/js/task-tracker.js
- tests/test_task_manager.py

Tests: `pytest -q` → **2044 passed in 69.10s** (was 2035 + 9 new
duration / logging assertions). `tests/test_task_manager.py` alone:
**42 passed in 0.20s**.

## Mapping diagnostics — verify SELECT permissions on every source table

Context: Mapping diagnostics validated entity / relationship JSON and
parsed SQL columns, but never asked the warehouse whether the **app's
own principal** could actually read the source tables. In production
(Databricks Apps mode) the app runs as an OAuth service principal that
needs explicit `SELECT` on each Unity Catalog table referenced by the
mapping; missing grants surfaced only later as opaque
`PERMISSION_DENIED` failures during VIEW creation in the Digital Twin
build. The fix adds a third diagnostic section that runs a
non-destructive `SELECT * FROM … LIMIT 0` against every distinct
source table and reports OK / missing-SELECT / not-found per table.

The extension reuses the existing accordion / KPI / `{check, status,
detail}` shape — both backend payload and frontend rendering — so the
new section is visually indistinguishable from the existing entity and
relationship sections, and the global Total / Passed / Warnings /
Errors KPI tiles already at the top of the page now include the
per-table results.

Changes:

1. src/back/objects/mapping/Mapping.py
   - `_FQN_TABLE_RE` and `_extract_fqn_from_sql(sql)` — regex helper
     that pulls every `catalog.schema.table` triple out of `FROM` /
     `JOIN` clauses (with or without backticks). Two-part references
     are intentionally skipped because they depend on the warehouse's
     default catalog/schema and cannot be probed unambiguously.
   - `_split_table_ref(value)` — parse `cat.sch.tbl` strings (the
     `source_table` / `target_table` columns on relationships) into a
     3-tuple, returning `None` for shorter names.
   - `_collect_source_tables()` — aggregates every distinct triple
     across non-excluded entities (explicit `catalog`+`schema`+`table`
     plus FQNs in `sql_query`) and relationships (`source_table` /
     `target_table` plus FQNs in `sql_query`), keeping a deduplicated
     list of human-readable referrers (`Entity: Person`,
     `Rel: assignedTo (source)`, `Rel: foo (sql)`) so the UI can show
     *why* each table is being checked.
   - `_classify_sql_error(exc)` — maps a warehouse exception message
     to `(status, detail)`, distinguishing `PERMISSION_DENIED`,
     `TABLE_OR_VIEW_NOT_FOUND`, `SCHEMA_NOT_FOUND`,
     `CATALOG_NOT_FOUND`, and a generic "Probe failed" fallback. We
     match on message substrings because the SDK does not expose
     typed Databricks error codes.
   - `_run_permission_checks(client)` — for each unique triple runs
     ``SELECT * FROM `cat`.`sch`.`tbl` LIMIT 0`` (zero rows fetched,
     full SELECT permission path exercised) and produces a
     `{table, referenced_by, status, check: "select", detail}` row.
     When `client` is `None` (no warehouse configured / local dev
     without PAT) returns a single `warning` advisory row so the UI
     explains why the section is empty rather than appearing broken.
   - `run_diagnostics(self, *, client=None)` — keyword-only `client`
     param, top-level `permissions` list added to the response, and
     the global `summary` rolls in the new ok / warnings / errors
     counts plus the row count in `total`.

2. src/api/routers/internal/mapping.py
   - `/mapping/diagnostics` route now depends on `Settings`, calls
     `get_databricks_client(domain, settings)` and runs the (blocking)
     diagnostics in a thread via the existing `run_blocking` helper so
     concurrent slow warehouse calls do not stall the FastAPI event
     loop.

3. src/front/templates/partials/mapping/_mapping_diagnostics.html
   - Third accordion item "Source table permissions" with
     `bi-shield-lock` icon, badge `#diagPermBadge`, and body
     container `#diagPermissionsBody`.

4. src/front/static/mapping/js/mapping-diagnostics.js
   - `_renderPermissionRow(perm)` — same collapsible card shape as
     entities/relationships, with table FQN as the label, comma-
     separated referrers as the truncated meta string, and the inner
     `<table.diag-checks-table>` row reusing the existing
     `_STATUS_ICON` palette.
   - `runDiagnostics()` reads `data.permissions || []`, fills the new
     body and updates the badge using the existing `_updateBadge`
     helper (so the badge colour matches worst-row severity).

5. tests/test_mapping_service.py
   - `_mock_domain` extended with an `ontology` kwarg + always sets
     `domain.ontology = {}` so the diagnostics path's
     `domain.ontology or {}` does not iterate over a MagicMock.
   - `TestExtractFqnFromSql`: backticked / `JOIN` / 2-part-skipped /
     empty input.
   - `TestSplitTableRef`: 3-part / backticked / short-returns-None.
   - `TestCollectSourceTables`: explicit triple, excluded entity
     skipped, relationship `source_table` / `target_table`,
     `sql_query` extraction, deduplicated referrers.
   - `TestClassifySqlError`: PERMISSION_DENIED, TABLE_OR_VIEW_NOT_FOUND,
     other.
   - `TestRunPermissionChecks`: `client=None` → warning row,
     no-tables → empty list, success path asserts the executed SQL is
     `SELECT … LIMIT 0` against the back-ticked FQN, error path
     classified as missing-SELECT.
   - `TestRunDiagnosticsPermissionsSection`: response shape, summary
     rolls up OKs and errors from the new section.

