## /health — real readiness probes; /health/detailed retired

Context: ``GET /health`` returned a hard-coded ``{"status":"healthy"}``
JSON dump with no behind-the-scenes verification of *anything*, so an
app that had lost its registry Volume binding, was missing
``CREATE VIEW`` on the registry schema, had no ``USAGE`` on the
Lakebase Postgres schema, or had run out of space in ``/tmp`` would
still report itself as healthy. The reciprocal route
``/health/detailed`` was a slightly more verbose copy of the same lie.
Operators (and load-balancer health probes) had no way to tell
whether the app could actually reach the dependencies it needs to
run. The user listed the precise checks they wanted in
``releasereq/TODO.md``: registry Volume, registry catalog/schema
write permissions for view materialisation, Lakebase, ``/tmp``
write+space; plus "any other permissions needed".

This change replaces the static endpoint with a real readiness probe
that exercises every external dependency the app actually uses, and
removes ``/health/detailed`` because the new payload covers the same
information in a single response. The route still returns HTTP 200
even when individual checks fail — external probes should look at
the top-level ``status`` (``ok`` / ``warning`` / ``error``) and
``summary.errors`` fields, so a single flickering dependency does
not yank the app out of rotation.

Probes implemented (in order):

1. **runtime** — Python + OntoBricks version (informational, always
   ``ok``).
2. **filesystem.tmp** — ``os.access`` write check, write+delete of a
   sentinel, ``shutil.disk_usage`` thresholds (warn <1 GB,
   error <100 MB).
3. **filesystem.session_dir** — same probe against
   ``settings.session_dir`` (``/tmp/ontobricks_session`` in Apps,
   ``./fastapi_session`` in dev).
4. **filesystem.log_dir** — resolved from ``LogManager.instance().log_path``.
5. **databricks.auth** — ``DatabricksAuth.has_valid_auth`` plus, in
   App mode, an active OAuth token mint via
   ``get_oauth_token`` so a bad ``DATABRICKS_CLIENT_ID``/
   ``CLIENT_SECRET`` fails here rather than in the next warehouse
   call.
6. **databricks.warehouse** — ``SQLWarehouse.test_connection``
   (``SELECT 1`` against the configured warehouse).
7. **registry.cfg** — ``RegistryCfg.from_domain(None, settings)``,
   asserts catalog/schema/volume are all resolved.
8. **registry.volume_read** — ``VolumeFileService.list_directory``
   on ``/Volumes/cat/sch/vol``.
9. **registry.volume_write** — writes a sentinel
   ``.health_check_<uuid>.txt`` then deletes it (real PUT through
   the same Files API the registry uses for ``.global_config.json``).
10. **registry.uc_schema_ddl** — ``CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW
    `cat`.`sch`.`_ontobricks_health_<uuid>` AS SELECT 1`` then
    ``DROP VIEW IF EXISTS``. This exercises the exact permission
    path the Digital-Twin build uses to materialise views, so a
    missing ``CREATE`` / ``USE_SCHEMA`` grant fails at startup
    rather than mid-build.
11. **lakebase** — when ``PG*`` env vars are bound, builds a
    ``LakebaseRegistryStore`` and calls ``init_status()``;
    ``no_usage`` / ``connect_failed`` map to ``error``,
    ``no_registries_table`` / ``no_registry_row`` map to
    ``warning`` (schema reachable, just not bootstrapped),
    ``ok`` maps to ``ok``. When PG\* env vars are absent the
    probe returns ``ok`` with "Lakebase not bound — registry uses
    Volume backend" so users on Volume backends do not see a
    spurious failure.

Each probe runs through ``_safely_run`` which wraps the body in a
``try/except`` and times it, so one broken probe never breaks the
whole response — the failure is shown next to the green checks
with a ``duration_ms`` and a clear detail message.

The whole readiness function is synchronous so individual probes can
make blocking SDK calls without ``await``; the FastAPI route wraps
it in the existing ``run_blocking`` helper so concurrent slow probes
do not stall the event loop.

Changes:

1. src/shared/fastapi/health.py
   - Full rewrite. Module-level constants ``_OK`` / ``_WARNING`` /
     ``_ERROR`` and a ``_SEVERITY_RANK`` table for the worst-of
     roll-up.
   - ``_safely_run(name, label, fn)`` runs each probe with timing
     and exception capture.
   - One private ``_check_*`` per probe (filesystem, auth, warehouse,
     registry cfg / volume read / volume write / UC DDL, Lakebase).
     Helpers depend on ``Settings`` (passed in) and the existing
     ``DatabricksAuth`` / ``DatabricksClient`` / ``VolumeFileService``
     / ``LakebaseRegistryStore`` / ``RegistryCfg.from_domain``
     plumbing — no new clients introduced.
   - ``run_readiness_checks(settings=None)`` aggregates and rolls
     up; ``health_check`` route hands off to ``run_blocking`` and
     returns ``{status, version, service, framework, summary, checks}``.
   - ``/health/detailed`` route removed.

2. tests/test_routes.py
   - ``TestHealthRoutes.test_health_check`` rewritten for the new
     shape: asserts the per-check schema (``name``, ``label``,
     ``status``, ``detail``, ``duration_ms``) and the top-level
     fields rather than the old static ``"healthy"`` literal.
   - ``test_detailed_health`` renamed to
     ``test_detailed_health_removed``, asserts ``404`` so the
     retirement is enforced.

3. tests/test_health.py (new)
   - Unit coverage with mocked dependencies so the probes run on
     CI machines with no Databricks credentials.
   - ``TestSafelyRun``: status passthrough + exception capture.
   - ``TestCheckDirectoryWritable``: ok / creates-missing / warn-
