## Fix — credential helpers crash on `domain=None`

Context: After the `/health` rewrite landed, the `databricks.warehouse`
probe failed with `'NoneType' object has no attribute 'databricks'`
even though the warehouse was correctly configured. Trace pointed at
`DatabricksHelpers.get_databricks_client(None, settings)` →
`domain.databricks.get(...)` — the helper assumed the HTTP request
lifecycle where a `DomainSession` is always present, but the readiness
probe (and any future session-less caller — MCP, scheduled jobs)
legitimately passes `domain=None`. `RegistryCfg.from_domain` already
handled the case; `DatabricksHelpers` had not been updated.

Three call sites blew up: `get_databricks_client`,
`get_databricks_host_and_token`, and `resolve_warehouse_id`. All
three now read the session config through a single
`_domain_databricks(domain)` helper that returns `{}` for
`domain is None` (or for a domain with no `databricks` attr), so the
existing fallthrough to `Settings`/env vars just works.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/helpers/DatabricksHelpers.py
   - New module-level `_domain_databricks(domain)` returning
     `getattr(domain, "databricks", None) or {}`, or `{}` when
     `domain is None`.
   - `resolve_warehouse_id`: replaced
     `domain.databricks.get("warehouse_id", "")` with
     `_domain_databricks(domain).get("warehouse_id", "")`.
   - `get_databricks_host_and_token`: replaced the two
     `domain.databricks.get(...)` reads with a single
     `dbcfg = _domain_databricks(domain)` upfront.
   - `get_databricks_client`: same — `dbcfg.get("host"|"token")` now
     accepts `domain=None`.

2. tests/test_helpers.py
   - `TestGetDatabricksHostAndToken.test_none_domain_falls_back_to_settings`:
     `get_databricks_host_and_token(None, settings)` returns the
     normalized Settings host + PAT.
   - New `TestNoneDomainSafety` class with three regression tests:
     `get_databricks_client(None, settings)`, `get_databricks_credentials(None, settings)`,
     and the no-creds variant returning `None`. Pins the contract so
     this regression cannot recur silently.

Modified files:
- src/back/core/helpers/DatabricksHelpers.py
- tests/test_helpers.py

Tests: `pytest -q` → **2101 passed in 65.64s** (was 2097 + 4 new
`domain=None` regression assertions).
`tests/test_helpers.py tests/test_health.py tests/test_routes.py::TestHealthRoutes`
together: **43 passed in 7.89s**. After the fix, the readiness probe's
`databricks.warehouse` row reports the warehouse's actual reachability
status instead of the `'NoneType'` traceback.


## Settings → Health tab

Context: After the `/health` rewrite earlier today, the readiness probe
returns a rich payload (overall status + per-check status / detail /
duration_ms for ~8 dependencies — `/tmp`, session dir, log dir,
Databricks auth, SQL warehouse, registry config, registry UC volume
read+write, registry UC schema DDL, Lakebase). Until now the only way
to consume that payload was a raw JSON GET on `/health`. The user
asked for an in-app surface so admins can run readiness checks from
the UI in one click.

Wired a new admin-only **Health** tab into the Settings page that
calls `GET /health`, drops the same KPI tiles used by Mapping
Diagnostics (Total / Passed / Warnings / Errors) and renders the
checks list as a sortable table (errors first, warnings second, ok
last) with status icon, label, name, detail and per-check duration.
Detail strings >200 chars collapse into a `<details>` to keep the
table compact.

Changes:

1. src/front/templates/partials/settings/_settings_health.html (new)
   - First file under the new `partials/settings/` directory. Header
     alert explains the probe semantics and links readers back to
     `GET /health` for external uptime probes. KPI tiles row reuses
     the global `ob-kpi-tile` / `tile-accent-*` classes loaded by
     `base.html` so no extra CSS is needed. Empty state placeholder
     spinner is shown until the first fetch resolves.

2. src/front/templates/settings.html
   - New `<li id="tab-health-wrapper">` nav-link inside the existing
     `{% if user_role == 'admin' %}` block (placed after Registry,
     so non-admins see no extra tab). New `<div id="pane-health">`
     `tab-pane` includes the partial. New
     `<script src=".../settings-health.js">` added to `extra_js`
     under the same admin guard.

3. src/front/static/config/js/settings-health.js (new)
   - Lazy-loads on `shown.bs.tab` of `#tab-health` (mirroring the
     Graph DB tab pattern) so the eight backend probes do not run
     for every Settings page open. Manual **Refresh** button hooks
     into the same `loadHealth()` entry point. Renders the overall
     status pill, KPI tiles, and a per-check table with severity
