## Domain / Build — live "Building Digital Twin" log panel

Context: When users clicked **Build** on the Domain / Build page they
got a single thin progress bar with one tiny status line. Long phases
(reading triples, writing triples in batches, archiving the graph)
all looked identical from the outside, with no per-step timing and no
visibility into what was actually happening for the 30–120 s the
build runs. Customers asked for a "what is it doing right now?"
panel — non-technical, chronological, with timings.

The fix adds a dedicated **Building Digital Twin** card directly
below the Digital Twin card. It appears on Build click and grows
row-by-row as the backend reports each phase. Each row shows the
phase description, a status icon, and a per-step elapsed time;
inside the running row a live sub-message shows fine-grained
progress like "Written 4500/15000 triples…". The information was
already produced by `TaskManager.advance_step` / `update_progress`
and exposed via `GET /tasks/{id}` — it just had no UI surface.

The change also fixes a pre-existing alignment bug between the
seeded step list and the actual execution: when the user forced a
**Full rebuild**, the backend skipped the *Checking source tables*
phase but `advance_step` still walked the step array by one, so the
"Creating view…" message landed in a row labelled "Checking source
tables". A new `TaskManager.skip_step()` marks unused phases as
`skipped` (greyed-out, "Not needed for this build") and keeps the
labels honest. Same logic when there's no snapshot yet — the
*Detecting what changed* row is correctly skipped on first build.

Changes:

1. src/back/core/task_manager/TaskManager.py
   - New `skip_step(task_id, message=None)` method. Marks the
     current step's `status="skipped"` with `started_at` and
     `completed_at` set to `now` (so the duration is "instant"),
     then advances `current_step` exactly like `advance_step`. Keeps
     the step array and the actual execution flow aligned even when
     phases are conditionally skipped.
   - `complete_task` no longer overwrites `skipped` steps with
     `completed`. The terminal sweep that filled in any leftover
     non-completed step now skips both `completed` *and* `skipped`,
     preserving the row's true history.

2. src/back/objects/digitaltwin/DigitalTwin.py
   - `run_build_task` calls `tm.skip_step(...)` for the *gate*
     phase when the user forced a full rebuild from the start, and
     for the *diff* phase when no snapshot exists or fallback to
     full has been decided. Each skip carries a short, plain-English
     reason ("Full rebuild requested — skipping change check",
     "No previous snapshot — full rebuild instead") that the panel
     surfaces under the row.
   - The "Applying changes to LadybugDB graph…" message becomes
     "Applying changes to the knowledge graph…" — same
     instrumentation point, just less internal-jargony in the UI.

3. src/api/routers/internal/dtwin.py
   - The seven seeded step descriptions on `/dtwin/sync/start` are
     rewritten to non-technical phrasing: "Preparing mappings and
     generating queries", "Checking source tables for new data",
     "Creating the Digital Twin view", "Detecting what changed
     since last build", "Updating the knowledge graph", "Saving a
     snapshot for next time", "Backing up the graph to the
